The Great Barrier Reef, located off the coast of Queensland, Australia, is a marvel of natural beauty and biodiversity. Stretching over 2,300 kilometers, it's the world's largest coral reef system. The reef is home to a stunning array of marine life, including over 1,500 species of fish and 400 types of coral. Snorkelers and divers from all over the world come to explore its crystal-clear waters, where they can witness the vibrant and diverse ecosystems beneath the surface.